          <li>• Gleneagles Hospital Medini</li>
          <li>• KPJ Johor Specialist</li>
          <li>• Columbia Asia Iskandar</li>
          <li>• Near Singapore (backup option)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Medical tourism:</strong> Malaysia is a top medical tourism destination. Procedures cost 50-80% less than Western countries with comparable quality. Many hospitals have dedicated international patient departments. Dental work, cosmetic surgery, and cardiac procedures are popular. Some expats time major procedures for Malaysia visits.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I get Malaysian citizenship through MM2H?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. MM2H is a long-term social visit pass, not a path to permanent residence or citizenship. Even after decades on MM2H, you remain a long-term visitor. Malaysia does not offer citizenship by investment. If citizenship matters, consider other countries.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happened to MM2H requirements in 2021?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Requirements increased dramatically: fixed deposit from RM300K to RM1M, monthly income from RM10K to RM40K, and liquid assets must now be RM1.5M. The changes were controversial and reduced applications significantly. Existing MM2H holders were grandfathered under old rules for renewals.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is S-MM2H (Sarawak) a good alternative?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, for many. Requirements are much lower (RM150K-300K deposit vs RM1M). You must reside primarily in Sarawak but can travel freely in Malaysia. Kuching is a pleasant city with good healthcare and lower costs. Popular with those who can't or won't meet federal requirements.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work on MM2H visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Limited work is possible. You can apply for a work endorsement for part-time work (20 hours/week max) in restricted sectors. Cannot compete with Malaysians. Remote work for overseas employers is generally tolerated but not explicitly authorized. For full work rights, consider Labuan or Employment Pass.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the minimum property price for foreigners?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Varies by state but typically RM1M or higher for foreigners. Some states have higher minimums. Strata titles (condos) are easier; landed property more restricted. Each state sets its own rules. Consult a property lawyer before purchasing. The RM300K affordable condos are for Malaysians only.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How does the fixed deposit work?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          You deposit RM1M (federal) or RM150K-300K (Sarawak) in a Malaysian bank as a condition of the visa. It earns interest (currently ~3-4%/year). After one year, you can withdraw 50% for approved purposes: property purchase, children's education, or medical expenses. Remaining 50% stays until you leave the program.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Malaysia's MM2H program remains attractive for those who can meet the higher requirements. English widely spoken, excellent healthcare, multicultural society, and affordable living make it a top choice for long-term residence. The 2021 changes disappointed many, but alternatives like S-MM2H offer more accessible entry points.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The trade-offs are clear: no citizenship pathway, increased financial requirements, and property restrictions. But for retirees and remote workers seeking comfortable, affordable Asian living with English proficiency, Malaysia delivers excellent value. Sarawak offers the original MM2H spirit at lower cost for those willing to embrace Borneo life.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      Health insurance is mandatory for MM2H participants aged 35+ and strongly recommended for all. Malaysia's private hospitals are excellent, but require payment or insurance guarantee. Budget RM500-2,500/month depending on coverage level and age.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        Malaysia suits investors and retirees seeking English-speaking, affordable SE Asian lifestyle with excellent healthcare. Federal MM2H requires substantial capital (RM1M deposit + RM40K/month income); S-MM2H offers accessible alternative (RM150K-300K). Come with realistic expectations about citizenship limits and property restrictions—but enjoy excellent value and quality of life.
      </p>
